THE LAND OF DAWN — NEO‑UKIYO‑E SUMI‑E WORLD MAP (16:9)
An epic, museum‑quality cartographic vision of the entire MLBB universe, factually accurate in geography and bursting with legendary landmarks, ancient silhouettes, and poetic calligraphy.

CANVAS & COMPOSITION
Generate a horizontal 16:9 image (1920×1080 pixels). This is a pure world map—there is no logo, no cartouche, no central emblem. The entire canvas is occupied by the continent of the Land of Dawn, rendered as an ancient, hand‑drawn cartographic scroll that fuses Neo‑Ukiyo‑e woodblock aesthetics with Zen Sumi‑e ink‑wash techniques and modern 8K hyper‑detail. The map is oriented with North at the top, West at the left, East at the right, and South at the bottom. The continent is surrounded by a vast, parchment‑toned ocean of reserved washi paper, its surface alive with subtle bokashi gradients of pale ivory, cream, and the faintest cerulean blue. The entire composition feels like a sacred artifact—a map that has been pored over by kings and demons alike for millennia.

THE NEO‑UKIYO‑E BORDER — CELESTIAL COMPASS RING
Encircling the entire map is a single, majestic Neo‑Ukiyo‑e border that functions as a divine compass rose and protective reliquary. Its outermost edge is a hairline of burnished 24K gold leaf, slightly irregular like genuine hand‑applied ohiromi gold, which gleams with specular highlights under an imagined celestial light. Immediately inside runs a continuous register of stylised ocean waves (seigaiha) rendered in raised silver‑blue lacquer, each wave crest tipped with a microscopic speck of phosphorescent foam. Dotting this wave band are tiny Vonetis Sea island silhouettes—each a single, masterful dry‑brush stroke of emerald‑green sumi, some with minute palm‑tree shapes and outrigger canoe silhouettes. At the four cardinal points, the wave band is interrupted by four ornate compass medallions: at the top (North), a snowflake‑crystal of the Northern Vale in frosted silver with a single glowing aurora wisp; at the right (East), a jade dragon of Cadia Riverlands coiled in raised gold with a tiny vermilion pearl in its claw; at the bottom (South), a sun‑disk of Agelta Drylands in amber and tarnished bronze, its rays spreading outward; and at the left (West), a cathedral‑spire of Moniyan in radiant gold, with a minuscule griffin perched atop. Between the four medallions, the wave band also features four secondary seasonal markers: a cherry‑blossom branch (spring, northeast), a lotus bloom (summer, southeast), a maple leaf (autumn, southwest), and a pine bough (winter, northwest). The innermost edge of the entire border is a serene, masterfully imperfect enso circle of warm charcoal‑grey sumi, its stroke bleeding gently into the parchment, representing the unity of all realms under the eternal sky.

THE MAP LAYOUT — FACTUALLY ACCURATE GEOGRAPHY OF THE LAND OF DAWN
The continent of the Land of Dawn occupies the central two‑thirds of the canvas, rising from the southern seas to the frozen northern coast. Its shape is organic and ancient, with jagged coastlines, deep bays, and a scattering of offshore islands. The geography follows the established lore precisely.

FAR NORTH — NORTHERN VALE (The Frozen Throne):
Occupying the entire top strip of the continent, from the northwest coast to the northeast, lies the Northern Vale, a realm of glacial white and pale cerulean ink wash. The Frozen Sea laps against the northern coast, depicted as a sheet of pale silver‑blue wash dotted with tiny iceberg silhouettes—each a single, sharp brushstroke of white sumi with a faint cyan under‑glow. Jutting from the northwest, Queen's Peak rises like a tower of ice, its snow‑capped summit lost in a ribbon of aurora borealis painted in translucent washes of cyan, violet, and pale emerald. The peak is rendered with sharp, angular dry‑brush strokes that suggest towering, cathedral‑like ice formations. In the centre‑north, the Megalith Wasteland—the borderland between the Vale and the Moniyan Empire—is depicted as a field of towering, angular stone spires drawn in dry‑brush charcoal grey and burnt sienna, their shadows long and ominous. The ground here is a distinctive crimson‑ochre wash, marking the famous red earth. The Great Martyr Shrine sits at the heart of the Vale, a tiny but sacred temple silhouette of raised silver with a single glowing gold spire, its entrance facing south toward the rest of Dawn. To the far east of the Vale, the mysterious Magic Academy is suggested by a single, floating spire of pale lavender ink, half‑hidden behind swirling snow‑mist and connected to the mainland by a thin, enchanted bridge of silver light. Along the northeastern coast, the port of Kastiya is marked by a tiny anchor symbol and a cluster of small, warm‑lit buildings. The region is labelled by elegant Japanese calligraphy:

北の谷 — 氷の玉座
[Northern Vale — The Frozen Throne]

CENTRE‑WEST — THE MONIYAN EMPIRE (The Radiant Heart):
Dominating the centre‑left of the continent, stretching from the western coast deep into the interior, lies the Moniyan Empire, the largest and most detailed region. Its heart is Lumina City, the imperial capital, rendered as a magnificent cluster of Gothic cathedral spires, domes, arched bridges, and fortified walls, all executed in raised gold‑leaf with obsessive architectural precision. Tiny stained‑glass rose windows are suggested by minuscule circles of ruby and sapphire lacquer. Radiating outward from Lumina City are thin, golden trade routes—the empire's arteries—connecting to every other major location. To the north of Lumina, Castle Grandrock stands as a formidable fortress atop a colossal stone plateau, its ramparts crenellated and its towers flying the imperial banner (a tiny gold cross on white). To the south, Castle Aberleen appears shrouded in pale, mysterious mist near the border with the Barren Lands, its spires more delicate and elegant. To the west, Castle Gorge marks the western capital, the second‑largest city, surrounded by tiny gold‑mine symbols and defensive walls. In the southeastern part of the Empire, the Azure Lake gleams as a perfect oval pool of cerulean‑silver wash, its surface mirror‑smooth and reflecting the sky; perched elegantly on its shore is Swan Castle, a delicate structure of white marble and silver. The Monastery of Light sits apart from the cities, a sanctuary of pure white architecture with a single, blindingly bright gold spire that emits tiny, painted rays of holy light. The Moniyan Plains stretch eastward as a vast golden‑green wash, dotted with tiny silhouette armies—knights on horseback, their lances raised, rendered as minuscule ink figures that suggest movement and life. The Black Forest and Braidwood appear as dense clusters of dark‑green and charcoal ink foliage, their edges soft and slightly foreboding. The Mossenia (Imperial Sanctuary) is marked by a ring of ancient standing stones near the empire's eastern border. Tiny griffin silhouettes soar over Lumina City.

中央帝国 — 光の守護者
[Central Empire — Guardian of Light]

CENTRE‑RIGHT — THE BARREN LANDS & NECROKEEP (The Land of Despair):
East of Moniyan, separated by the colossal Lantis Mountains, lies the tragic Barren Lands, occupying the centre‑right of the map. The Lantis Mountains form the longest mountain range on the continent, rendered as a jagged spine of charcoal‑grey ink with snow‑capped peaks of reserved white paper; they curve southward like a protective wall, isolating the Empire from the corruption to the east. The mountains are dotted with tiny Grock silhouettes—ancient stone guardians. The Barren Lands themselves are a scar of charcoal‑black and blood‑crimson ink wash, a once‑fertile land now blighted. The Necrokeep—the Fortress of Despair, ruled by Duchess Vexana—dominates the region's centre, a jagged, skeletal fortress of obsidian spires and broken ramparts, rendered in sharp, angry dry‑brush strokes. Tiny, ghostly wraith silhouettes (Vexana's spectral army) drift around its towers. The Askati Forest clings to life as a cluster of impossibly tall, twisted trees rendered in pale grey ink with dark, finger‑like branches that seem to claw at the sky. The Despair Place is a barren, cracked plain of pale ochre, while the Stormeye Wasteland swirls with a permanent, miniature vortex of ink‑wash storm clouds. The Rantha Mountains form a secondary, smaller range to the south. The entire region is wreathed in a thin, permanent mist of diluted charcoal wash, and a single, ghostly Pharsa silhouette (a great bird of prey) circles above Necrokeep.

絶望の地 — 影の砦
[Land of Despair — Fortress of Shadows]

FAR EAST — THE SHADOW ABYSS (The Kingdom of Darkness):
Beyond the Lantis Mountains and the Barren Lands, occupying the entire far‑eastern side of the continent, lies the Shadow Abyss—the hideous scar carved into the world. This region is a terrifying, beautiful void rendered in deepest indigo‑black sumi with veins of glowing cyan and sickly green mana running through it like cracks in reality. The Crack of the Abyss is a colossal, vertical fissure that splits the land, glowing with cold cyan bioluminescence; from its depths, faint, twisted shapes seem to reach upward. The Sanguine Lair—Alice's domain—appears as a pool of glossy vermilion‑black ink, from which thorned tendrils spread outward like creeping veins, each thorn tipped with a tiny drop of blood‑red lacquer. The Molten Realm—Thamuz's volcanic territory—is a fiery scar of crimson‑orange wash at the Abyss's southern edge, with rivers of lava flowing into the sea and tiny Thamuz silhouettes (winged, scythe‑armed demons) standing guard. The Night Palace—Obsidia's dark throne—rises at the Abyss's heart as a jagged, upside‑down obsidian cathedral, its spires pointing downward into the void, surrounded by a halo of cold cyan flame. The Abyssal Dragon's silhouette coils across the entire region, its colossal spine forming a mountain range of bone‑white ink; its skull‑like head rests near the Crack, jaws open as if exhaling the darkness itself. Tiny demonic swarms—winged shadows, horned figures, and coiling serpents—drift across the Abyss like smoke. The region is labelled:

深淵 — 影の王国
[The Abyss — Kingdom of Shadows]

FAR SOUTH‑WEST — AGELTA DRYLANDS (The Sun‑Scorched Expanse):
Occupying the entire lower‑left quadrant of the continent, a vast expanse of warm ochre, burnt sienna, and dusty gold ink wash stretches from the western coast deep into the interior: the Agelta Drylands. The Emerald Road—the ancient trade route—cuts diagonally through the desert like a faded scar, rendered as a thin, dashed line of pale jade ink with tiny ruined city‑state silhouettes dotting its length. Wind Fort appears as a fortified garrison of sandstone, its towers shaped by centuries of desert wind. Fire Throat—the volcanic forge‑city—is rendered as a crater of glowing amber and crimson, with tiny anvil symbols and smoke plumes. The Ruins of Tivacan appear near the western coast as a haunting cluster of broken columns, shattered domes, and half‑buried statues, with the faint, sealed silhouette of Khufra's tomb glowing a sickly amber at its deepest point. The Minoan Labyrinth is a spiralling maze carved into the earth, rendered as a series of interlocking, concentric dry‑brush circles with a tiny Minotaur silhouette at its heart. The Stargate Valley sits in the desert's interior, its celestial observatories drawn as tiny, precise domes of gold‑leaf connected by thin lines that mirror constellations. Los Pecados—the city of outlaws—is a rough cluster of adobe structures near the southern edge. The Oasis created by Belerick glows as a small, perfect circle of emerald‑green surrounded by palm silhouettes. The Western Expanse fades into the edge of the map as a trackless sea of dunes. At the desert's northeastern edge, adjacent to Moniyan, the Foggy Mountains (Misty Mountains) form a natural barrier, their peaks a soft wash of grey‑white ink. The Eruditio city‑state sits precisely at the mid‑west, north of the desert proper, its brass spires and floating gears rising in a cluster of copper‑gold, connected by thin arcs of purple‑white lightning; tiny airship silhouettes drift around it. The region is labelled:

西の砂漠 — 太陽の目
[Western Desert — The Eye of the Sun]

SOUTH‑CENTRE — AZRYA WOODLANDS (The Moonlit Realm):
Nestled between Moniyan, the Barren Lands, and the southern coast, the Azrya Woodlands occupies the south‑centre of the map. This region is a lush, enchanted forest rendered in emerald‑green, moon‑silver, and deep viridian ink washes. The Moonlit Forest spreads across most of the region as a sea of stylised oak‑leaf patterns, each leaf a tiny, precise brushstroke, with beams of silver moonlight (rendered as translucent negative‑space shafts) piercing through the canopy. At the forest's heart, the Lunar Temple glows—a delicate, crescent‑shaped structure of silver‑leaf and ancient stone, surrounded by concentric rings of pale moonlight; it is the holiest site of the Moon Elves, where the goddess Gavana sleeps. The Shadow Swamp—the corrupted, dark part of Azrya—appears as a sickly stain of murky indigo and black at the Woodlands' eastern edge, near the Barren Lands, its trees twisted and weeping. The Enchanted Forest shimmers with tiny, glowing motes of cyan and gold. The Dark Forest is a foreboding cluster of ancient, towering trees with trunks of charcoal ink. Tiny elf‑silhouettes—archers with drawn bows, stags with grand antlers, and moon‑priestesses (Miya) in flowing robes—move through the trees. The Moonlake reflects the temple's light as a still, silver pool.

月の森 — 生命の樹
[Moon Forest — The Tree of Life]

OFFSHORE EAST — CADIA RIVERLANDS (The Dragon Isles):
Separated from the main continent by a band of pale jade sea (the Sea of Hope), the Cadia Riverlands occupies the far‑eastern edge of the map as a distinct island continent, correctly placed across the sea. This realm is a harmonious wash of jade‑green, pale gold, crimson, and mountain‑blue ink. The Dragon Altar sits at its mountainous heart, a tiered pagoda of gold‑leaf and silver, encircled by the coiled silhouette of the Great Dragon, its body a winding river of raised gold lacquer that spirals around the altar; the altar is enshrouded in cloud‑mist, making it almost invisible to the outside world. The Forbidden Area of Dragon Soul is a mist‑shrouded mountain peak glowing with an inner emerald light, sealed and forbidden. Jaguar Peak, Sky Arch, and Stream Valley are rendered as delicate, named landscape features in pale ink. The City of the Dragon—the port city in the north, ruled by Empress Zetian—appears as a cluster of oriental palace‑roofs, arched bridges, and bustling harbour silhouettes. Tiny phoenix silhouettes sweep across the sky, their tails single, sweeping vermilion brushstrokes. Yu Zhong's Black Dragon silhouette lurks in the southern mountains, coiled and menacing. The region is labelled:

東方列島 — 龍の川
[Eastern Isles — The Dragon's River]

FAR SOUTH — VONETIS ISLANDS (The Beautiful Archipelago):
Scattered across the southern seas, below Agelta, Azrya, and the Abyss, lies the Vonetis Sea, a tropical archipelago rendered as a scattering of emerald‑green and golden islands floating in pale turquoise wash. Each island is a tiny, unique silhouette: some with palm‑like trees, others with small village huts and port structures. Perlas, the central island and trade hub, is marked by a cluster of port buildings and tiny ship silhouettes. Blue Flame Island in the north of the archipelago is shrouded in a permanent, translucent blue mist that glows faintly. Baker Island to the south of Agelta features a small, ominous research base. Tiny outrigger canoes, sea‑serpent silhouettes, and the distinctive Lapu‑Lapu warrior silhouette (a proud figure with twin blades) drift across the waters. The region is labelled:

南洋の島々 — 楽園の海
[Southern Islands — Sea of Paradise]

CARTOGRAPHIC DETAILS — TRADE ROUTES, COMPASS, & SCALE
Thin, elegant gold‑leaf trade routes crisscross the continent, connecting Lumina City to Eruditio, to the Northern Vale ports, to the City of the Dragon, and to Perlas. Sea routes are marked by dotted gold lines with tiny ship silhouettes. A large, ornate compass rose sits in the lower‑right corner of the ocean, its eight points rendered in gold and silver with vermilion tips. A scale bar in the lower‑left corner is rendered as a delicate, measured line of gold with tiny Moniyan script numerals. In each ocean, sea monsters drawn in the style of medieval cartographic marginalia—coiling serpents, breaching whales, and the silhouettes of the Abyssal Sea Dragon—swim among the waves, their forms suggested by masterful, single‑stroke sumi lines. The Twilight Orb—the source of so much conflict—is suggested as a tiny, glowing point of gold and violet light hovering ambiguously between Moniyan and the Abyss, its exact location deliberately uncertain.

JAPANESE CALLIGRAPHY — EIGHT REGIONAL INVOCATIONS
Eight vertical columns of Japanese calligraphy are placed with ritual precision around the map, each near its corresponding region. They are executed in a bold, semi‑cursive gyōsho script using an ink of gold‑flecked obsidian. A tiny vermilion woodblock‑stamp English translation sits directly below each column in delicate brackets, the text crisp and slightly distressed, as if stamped by an ancient cartographer's seal.

光の帝国は永遠に輝く (near Moniyan)
[The Empire of Light shines eternal]

砂漠の目はすべてを見通す (near Agelta)
[The Desert's Eye sees all]

氷の玉座は勇者を待つ (near Northern Vale)
[The Frozen Throne awaits a hero]

龍と共に運命を流れよ (near Cadia Riverlands)
[Flow with destiny alongside the Dragon]

月の森が古の歌を囁く (near Azrya Woodlands)
[The Moon Forest whispers ancient songs]

影が覚醒し、深淵が呼ぶ (near the Abyss)
[The shadows awaken, the Abyss calls]

絶望の地を越えて光を見出せ (near Barren Lands)
[Beyond the Land of Despair, find the light]

南洋の島々で伝説が生まれる (near Vonetis Islands)
[In the southern isles, legends are born]

Every character displays the physical truth of woodblock printing: subtle embossment, the tiniest ink‑squeeze at stroke terminations, and visible washi paper fibre beneath the strokes. The vermilion stamps are slightly chalky and matte, like genuine cinnabar paste.

COLOR PALETTE, LIGHTING & ATMOSPHERE
The palette spans the entire emotional range of the Land of Dawn: burnished gold for Moniyan; deep indigo and cyan for the Abyss; warm ochre and amber for Agelta; glacial white and silver for the Northern Vale; jade, crimson, and gold for Cadia; emerald and moon‑silver for Azrya; charcoal and blood‑red for the Barren Lands; and turquoise, emerald, and cream for the Vonetis Sea. The oceans are a shifting blend of pale cerulean, cream parchment, and silver. Lighting emanates from a soft, diffuse celestial source above the map's centre, as if the entire Land of Dawn is illuminated by a gentle, divine sun. Each region catches this light differently: gold glints on Moniyan's spires, cold cyan pulses in the Abyss's veins, warm amber glows on the desert dunes, silver sparkles on the northern ice, and moonlight bathes the Azrya Woodlands. A thin, volumetric mist of translucent ivory wash drifts across the oceans and mountain ranges, unifying the map without obscuring a single detail.

FINAL RENDERING DIRECTIVES
Generate in 4K HD, 16:9 aspect ratio, with ultra‑realistic, 8K‑grade texture fidelity. The style is an uncompromising masterwork fusion of Neo‑Ukiyo‑e woodblock technique, Zen Sumi‑e ink‑wash cartography, and medieval mappa mundi aesthetics, elevated by modern cinematic lighting. Every single landmark—from Lumina City's rose windows to the Dragon Altar's pagoda, from Queen's Peak's icy spires to the Crack of the Abyss's cyan fissure, from the Minoan Labyrinth's spirals to the Vonetis canoes—must be tangible, crisp, and awe‑inspiring. The map must feel like a sacred artifact, a cartographic treasure that kings and demons have fought over for millennia. No anime smoothness, no cartoon softness—only the museum‑quality beauty of a sacred world map, alive with history and legend. The artwork breathes a single, grand invitation: This is the Land of Dawn. Every realm, every legend, every battle—etched forever. Where will your story begin?







LEGENDARY BEASTS OF THE LAND OF DAWN — 16:9 NEO‑UKIYO‑E BESTIARY MAP
(Upload your world map image as a strict reference for the continent shape, coastlines, and all regional boundaries.)

1. REFERENCE IMAGE & GEOGRAPHICAL FIDELITY
Take the uploaded world map image as an absolute geographical stencil for the entire Land of Dawn continent. The exact shape of the mainland, the offshore Cadia Riverlands, the Vonetis Archipelago, and all coastlines, mountain ranges, and regional divisions must be preserved with 100% accuracy. Do not alter, move, or distort any landmass, island, sea, or border. The only transformation permitted is a thematic one: the map must now become a legendary bestiary cartograph, where every region is populated by the silhouettes and detailed forms of its most iconic mythical beasts, drawn in the same epic scale as the geography itself. The map must remain instantly recognizable as your original world map, now alive with the creatures of legend.

2. CANVAS & COMPOSITION
Generate a 16:9 horizontal image (1920×1080 pixels). The entire Land of Dawn continent fills the central canvas, surrounded by the parchment‑toned oceans. The map is a bestiary scroll—an ancient, illuminated manuscript page that fuses geography with mythology. Every region is clearly delineated, and each is dominated by one or more colossal, beautifully detailed legendary beasts, depicted in the act of guarding, soaring, or slumbering. The map’s title and poetic invocations float in the sky. All regions and beasts are labelled in elegant English cartographic script.

3. STYLE: NEO‑UKIYO‑E WITH SUMI‑E INK WASH (THE AESTHETIC OF LIVING MYTH)
The entire map is rendered in an uncompromising fusion of Neo‑Ukiyo‑e woodblock aesthetics and Zen Sumi‑e ink‑wash techniques, now elevated to depict living legends. The brushwork ranges from the precise, feather‑fine strokes of griffin wings to the bold, sweeping wet‑brush of a dragon’s coiling body. The land itself is rendered in subtle, faded washes to allow the beasts to dominate. The parchment base is a warm, aged ivory, as if this map has been pored over by generations of scholars and adventurers. Raised gold lacquer is used for celestial beasts, silver for winter spirits, crimson and vermilion for phoenix fire, jade for river dragons, and deep indigo for abyssal horrors. Every beast is executed with 8K‑grade texture fidelity, each scale, feather, and antler hyper‑detailed, feeling simultaneously like a sacred temple scroll and a living, breathing world of myth.

4. THE NEO‑UKIYO‑E BORDER — THE BESTIARY RING
The map is enclosed in a single, majestic border that celebrates all creatures. Its outermost edge is a hairline of burnished bronze, warm and ancient. Inside runs a continuous register of interwoven animal motifs rendered in raised lacquer: griffin wings, dragon scales, phoenix tail feathers, kirin antlers, frost‑wyrm coils, and sea‑serpent fins, all seamlessly flowing into one another. At the four cardinal corners, the border blossoms into ornate, beast‑themed compass medallions: the Celestial Griffon (northwest), the Jade Dragon (northeast), the Nine‑Tailed Fox (southwest), and the Abyssal Serpent (southeast). The innermost edge is a serene enso circle of warm charcoal sumi, its stroke slightly wild, as if brushed by the claw of a dragon—a meditation on the untamed spirit of the world.

5. THE BEASTS OF THE LAND OF DAWN — REGION BY REGION
Each region of the continent is vividly populated by its legendary guardians.

Northern Vale (Top): Soaring above Queen’s Peak and the Frozen Sea is the Celestial Ice Phoenix, a titanic bird of pale silver and cyan, wings spread wide, trailing the aurora borealis behind it. Coiling around the peak itself is the Frost Wyrm, a serpent of glacial scales and icy breath. A tiny, distant herd of Spirit Stags runs across the Megalith Wasteland.

Moniyan Empire (Centre‑West): Over Lumina City, the Imperial Griffon dominates the sky—a colossal, winged lion with eagle’s head, rendered in burnished gold and silver, its feathers individually embossed. A second, smaller griffin soars near Castle Grandrock. A Celestial Lion (the Lionheart) sleeps on the Moniyan Plains. A Holy Unicorn stands at the edge of the Braidwood.

Cadia Riverlands (Far East Island): The Great Dragon coils around the Dragon Altar in a spiraling, raised‑gold body, its whiskers flowing like calligraphy. A Vermilion Phoenix soars above, its tail a sweeping arc of crimson and orange splatter. A Kirin stands on a distant peak, its silver antlers catching the dawn.

Azrya Woodlands (South‑Centre): The King Stag—a colossal white elk with antlers like an ancient tree—stands at the heart of the Moonlit Forest, bathed in a silver beam. A Nine‑Tailed Fox sits curled beneath the Tree of Life, her tails a cascade of flowing ink. Tiny Sprite‑Owl silhouettes flit through the canopies.

Agelta Drylands (South‑West): The immense Sand Wyrm—the Agelta Great Serpent—coils through the desert, its body a series of dune‑like curves of ochre and bronze. The Sphinx crouches atop the Ruins of Tivacan, its stone body half‑buried, its eyes glowing amber. A Giant Scorpion guards the Minoan Labyrinth.

Shadow Abyss (Far East): The Abyssal Dragon sprawls across the entire region, its bone‑white spine forming a secondary mountain range, its skull resting near the Crack of the Abyss. The Infernal Hellhound (Cerberus) guards the Molten Realm. A colossal Bat Demon hangs from the Night Palace.

Barren Lands & Necrokeep (Centre‑Right): The Spectral Undead King—a colossal, ghostly knight—stands above Necrokeep, his greatsword planted. The Pharsa (Great Bird of Sorrow) circles the Askati Forest, a single cyan tear falling. A Wraith‑Wyrm coils through the Despair Place.

Vonetis Sea & Archipelago (South): The Great Sea‑Spirit Whale breaches, its body a masterful single‑stroke sumi wash. A gentle Sea‑Serpent Guardian coils around Perlas. Tiny Flying Fish and a Giant Manta Ray drift through the turquoise waters. The warrior Lapu‑Lapu stands on an outrigger, his silhouette accompanied by a spectral Shark Spirit.

Lantis Mountains (Central Spine): Along the great divide, the ancient Stone Golems (Grock) stand sentinel, their bodies cracked but unbroken. A pair of Mountain Wyverns duel in the high passes.

Eruditio (Mid‑West): A Mechanical Dragon—a construct of brass and arcane energy—hovers protectively over the City of Progress, its wings made of interlocking gears.

